sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects modification of the registry settings used for Internet Explorer and other Windows components that use these settings. An attacker can abuse this registry key to add a domain to the trusted sites Zone or insert javascript for persistence

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Msiexec.EXE Initiated Network Connection Over HTTP
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects an initiated network connection by "Msiexec.exe" over port 80 or 443.
Adversaries might abuse "msiexec.exe" to install and execute remotely hosted packages.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Script Initiated Connection to Non-Local Network
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects a script interpreter wscript/cscript opening a network connection to a non-local network. Adversaries may use script to download malicious payloads.
Detects a rundll32 that communicates with public IP addresses
Detects execution of "rundll32.exe" with a parent process of Explorer.exe. This has been observed by variants of Raspberry Robin, as first reported by Red Canary.

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Unsigned DLL Loaded by Windows Utility
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects windows utilities loading an unsigned or untrusted DLL.
Adversaries often abuse those programs to proxy execution of malicious code.
Detects modification of autostart extensibility point (ASEP) in registry.
sigma_analysis_results.rule_author: Victor Sergeev, Daniil Yugoslavskiy, Gleb Sukhodolskiy, Timur Zinniatullin, oscd.community, Tim Shelton, frack113 (split)

Adversaries may configure system settings to automatically execute a program during system boot or logon to maintain persistence or gain higher-level privileges on compromised systems.
Adversaries may achieve persistence by adding a program to a startup folder or referencing it with a Registry run key.
Adversaries may attempt to hide artifacts associated with their behaviors to evade detection.

Adversaries may attempt to get information about running processes on a system.
Adversaries may interact with the Windows Registry to gather information about the system, configuration, and installed software.
Adversaries may communicate using application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic.
